# =============================================================================
# CoreFirst — fully-local stack for 16 GB machines (Mac M-series / Windows)
#
# All providers run locally — no cloud API key required.
#
# RAM budget at peak (text + TTS + STT sidecars):
#   qwen2.5:14b q4_K_M  ~9 GB
#   Kokoro Docker        ~0.5 GB
#   faster-whisper-small ~0.5 GB
#   OS + browser         ~3 GB
#   ─────────────────── ~13 GB   ← safe on 16 GB
#
# Image generation (ComfyUI, separate process, runs after text is idle):
#   SD 1.5   +4 GB  (total ~13 GB, safe to run alongside text model)
#   SDXL     +7 GB  (total ~16 GB, tight — may need to close other apps)
#
# vs. the 64 GB config:
#   - Text model: 14b q4 instead of 32b q4 — noticeably weaker on complex
#     course generation; fine for roleplay and speech eval.
#   - Image: ComfyUI instead of Ollama z-image-turbo, because z-image-turbo
#     needs ~12 GB and cannot coexist with a 9 GB text model in RAM.
#   - Transform / courseGen: no cloud-model override — same 14b local model.
# =============================================================================

# GLOBAL_PROVIDER=
# GLOBAL_API_KEY=


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Text — Ollama (14b q4_K_M is the largest model that fits alongside TTS/STT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pull once:
#   ollama pull qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M
#
# Alternatives if quality is insufficient:
#   ollama pull gemma3:12b          # 8 GB, Google's instruction model, strong at creative tasks
#   ollama pull phi4:14b            # 9 GB, Microsoft, excellent reasoning
#
# ── Split-model option (advanced) ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Routing heavy vs. real-time tasks to different models can improve throughput,
# but on 16 GB it has a hidden cost: Ollama must evict and reload a 9 GB model
# every time the active task switches — a 10–20 s pause each swap.
# Only worth it if CourseGen and Roleplay are never running concurrently.
#
#   Heavy tasks (quality-critical, latency-tolerant):
#     TRANSFORM_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M   # ~9 GB
#     COURSE_GEN_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M
#
#   Real-time tasks (latency-sensitive, lighter load):
#     ROLEPLAY_MODEL=phi4-mini:3.8b                  # ~2.5 GB, fast
#     SPEECH_EVAL_MODEL=phi4-mini:3.8b
#     # ollama pull phi4-mini
#
# Bottom line: single 14b model is simpler and avoids swap pauses.
# Switch to split only after confirming the swap cost is acceptable on your machine.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
TEXT_PROVIDER=ollama
OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://localhost:11434
OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M

# Quality-critical features reuse the same local model.
# (The 64 GB config overrides these with gpt-oss:120b-cloud; skip that here.)
TRANSFORM_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M
COURSE_GEN_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M

# Latency-sensitive features
ROLEPLAY_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M
SPEECH_EVAL_MODEL=qwen2.5:14b-instruct-q4_K_M


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TTS — Kokoro via Docker sidecar (same as 64 GB config, ~250 MB)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Start (or use docker compose up):
#   docker run -d --name corefirst-kokoro -p 8880:8880 \
#     ghcr.io/remsky/kokoro-fastapi-cpu:latest
#
# Verify:
#   curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8880/v1/audio/speech \
#     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
#     -d '{"model":"kokoro","input":"hello","voice":"af_sky"}' \
#     --output /tmp/test.wav && open /tmp/test.wav
TTS_PROVIDER=openai
TTS_MODEL=kokoro
TTS_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8880/v1
TTS_VOICE=af_sky                # voices: af_sky, af_bella, af_sarah, am_adam, am_michael, bf_emma, bm_george…


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STT — faster-whisper-small via Docker sidecar (same as 64 GB config, ~500 MB)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Start (or use docker compose up):
#   docker run -d --name corefirst-faster-whisper -p 8000:8000 \
#     -e WHISPER__MODEL=Systran/faster-whisper-small \
#     -v ~/.cache/huggingface:/root/.cache/huggingface \
#     fedirz/faster-whisper-server:latest-cpu
#
# Verify:
#   curl http://localhost:8000/v1/audio/transcriptions \
#     -F "file=@some-audio.wav" -F "model=Systran/faster-whisper-small"
STT_PROVIDER=openai
STT_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000/v1
STT_MODEL=small
STT_API_KEY=local


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Image — ComfyUI (native, no API key, ~4–7 GB depending on model)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why not Ollama z-image-turbo:
#   z-image-turbo needs ~12 GB. On a 16 GB machine it cannot share RAM with the
#   14b text model. ComfyUI + SD 1.5 uses only ~4 GB and runs concurrently.
#
# Setup (one-time):
#   1. Install ComfyUI: https://github.com/comfyanonymous/ComfyUI
#      macOS: `pip install comfyui` or use the desktop launcher
#      Windows: use the portable .exe release
#
#   2. Install the OpenAI-compatible API extension:
#      cd ComfyUI/custom_nodes
#      git clone https://github.com/andreasjansson/ComfyUI-API
#      (any plugin that exposes POST /v1/images/generations on port 8188)
#
#   3. Download a checkpoint into ComfyUI/models/checkpoints/:
#      Model             Size   RAM needed   Notes
#      ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#      v1-5-pruned-emaonly.safetensors   ~4 GB   ~5 GB   SD 1.5, fast
#      sd_xl_base_1.0.safetensors        ~7 GB   ~8 GB   SDXL, better quality
#      flux1-schnell-fp8.safetensors     ~8 GB   ~9 GB   Flux, best quality
#      ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#      Recommended for 16 GB: sd_xl_base_1.0 (safe) or flux1-schnell-fp8 (better, tight)
#
#   4. Start ComfyUI (default port 8188)
#
# Verify:
#   curl -s http://localhost:8188/v1/images/generations \
#     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
#     -d '{"model":"sd_xl_base_1.0.safetensors","prompt":"a sunny classroom","size":"1024x1024","response_format":"b64_json"}' \
#     | python3 -c 'import sys,json,base64; d=json.load(sys.stdin); open("/tmp/test.png","wb").write(base64.b64decode(d["data"][0]["b64_json"]))' \
#     && open /tmp/test.png
IMAGE_GEN_PROVIDER=comfyui
IMAGE_GEN_MODEL=sd_xl_base_1.0.safetensors
# IMAGE_GEN_MODEL=v1-5-pruned-emaonly.safetensors   # lighter, use if SDXL is too slow
# IMAGE_GEN_MODEL=flux1-schnell-fp8.safetensors     # best quality, tight on 16 GB
# IMAGE_GEN_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8188           # default; change if using a different port


# =============================================================================
# Operating notes
# =============================================================================
# 1. Service startup order: Ollama → Kokoro Docker → faster-whisper Docker →
#    Next.js dev server. The Next process resolves models lazily.
#
# 2. Start Docker sidecars with one command (from project root):
#      docker compose up -d
#
# 3. Quick teardown:
#      docker compose down
#
# 4. If course generation output quality is unsatisfactory, consider routing
#    Transform / courseGen to a cloud provider while keeping the rest local:
#      TRANSFORM_PROVIDER=google
#      TRANSFORM_MODEL=gemini-2.5-pro
#      GOOGLE_GENERATIVE_AI_API_KEY=...
#      COURSE_GEN_PROVIDER=google
#      COURSE_GEN_MODEL=gemini-2.5-pro
#
# 5. Ollama model eviction: Ollama unloads a model after 5 min of inactivity
#    (OLLAMA_KEEP_ALIVE=5m). Image generation (ComfyUI) runs in a separate
#    process and does not affect Ollama's RAM — they coexist safely.
#
# 6. Windows + NVIDIA GPU: install CUDA toolkit, then Ollama and ComfyUI both
#    pick it up automatically. No extra configuration needed here.
